DOS-PORT (patch 0088, Phase 9 wave 20). Polarity flip of patch 0086.
Wave 18 shipped DIRECT_VESA default-OFF as an experimental opt-in.
Real-HW measurement (wave 18 W18A.LOG / W18B.LOG) confirmed:
  - 100/100 attempted presents engaged the direct path, 0 failures
  - +0.27 fps title on banked path
  - +0.65 fps title on LFB path (FORCE_LFB=1 stack)
  - No visual regressions in any tested scene (title / cmod / dialog)

Per memory/wave_18_sdl_overhead_closed.md the SDL-layer dispatch cost
hypothesis is closed at ~1.1 ms/flip — the direct path saves exactly
that much. Small but free, and "free" matters when the wave-19
display-contention hypothesis closed at 0 fps and the gap to the
revised 30 fps KPI is 4.4 fps (per memory/main_kpi_framerate.md).

Wave 20 promotes this from opt-in to DEFAULT-ON. The
SDL_HINT_DOSKUTSU_DIRECT_VESA env var keeps its name but inverts its
semantics:
  - default (unset / empty / "1" / any non-"0"): direct-VESA ENGAGED
  - "0" (literal): killswitch reverts to wave-17.6 baseline path
    (SDL_RenderPresent + SDL_UpdateWindowSurface)

This is the inverse of wave-16+ "strict 1-only enables" convention.
The killswitch convention mirrors wave-17.6 patch 0085 (PREVFRAME_DIFF
default-ON -> default-OFF after regression surfaced) — a single env
var lets a user revert to bisect-able prior behaviour without a
rebuild. Documented in docs/BOOT.md (re-categorized from "Diagnostic /
development" to "Compatibility / fallback").

Implementation is a 36-line diff in src/graphics/Renderer.cpp:
  1. _abl_direct_vesa() helper body: changed from
     `_strict_truthy_env("SDL_HINT_DOSKUTSU_DIRECT_VESA")` to inline
     `!(e && e[0]=='0' && e[1]==0)` lambda. Strict killswitch — any
     other value (including unset) keeps the path ON.
  2. Renderer::initVideo log emission: ENABLED / DISABLED branches
     swap their default messaging. The DISABLED branch now references
     the killswitch instead of the opt-in.
  3. No code changes in flip() — patch 0086's gate (_abl_direct_vesa()
     && !first_n_force && !_force_full_refresh) reads the same way;
     only the helper's polarity changed.

What stays unchanged from 0086:
  - First-N-frames force fallthrough (init backbuffer undefined)
  - _force_full_refresh fallthrough (flushAll, scene reset)
  - SDL/0034 generation counter R2 mitigation
  - Phase-timing diagnostic block format ([direct-vesa: ...])
  - DEBUG.LOG snapshot line on first eligible flip

Risk: low. The path itself is identical to 0086's; only the gate's
default flips. If a regression surfaces on a fingerprint we haven't
tested (e.g. a Cirrus variant other than 5434, a non-Mach64 / non-
Cirrus PCI VESA card), the user can SET SDL_HINT_DOSKUTSU_DIRECT_VESA=0
and reboot to recover the wave-17.6 baseline. The wave-18 measurement
already covered the two main g2k-machine-flavored configs (banked
default + LFB-forced).

Test plan (task #6 wave-20 W20B 2-PLAY ablation iter):
  - PLAY1.BAT: default config (no env vars) — should reproduce wave-18
    PLAY2 fps figure (+0.27 fps over wave-17.6 baseline on banked).
  - PLAY2.BAT: SET SDL_HINT_DOSKUTSU_DIRECT_VESA=0 — should reproduce
    wave-17.6 baseline fps (25.6 title) confirming killswitch reverts.
  - Visual A/B between PLAY1 and PLAY2: both must render correctly.
  - Phase-timing block grep: PLAY1 should show non-zero presents=N;
    PLAY2 should show presents=0 with DIRECT_VESA=0 ablation flag.

Reference:
  patches/nxengine-evo/0086-perf-wave-18-direct-vesa-hotpath.patch
  patches/nxengine-evo/0085-perf-wave-17-6-prev-frame-diff-default-off.patch
